				"richText": {
					"type": "doc",
					"attrs": {
						"dir": "auto"
					},
					"content": [
						{
							"type": "paragraph",
							"attrs": {
								"dir": "auto"
							},
							"content": [
								{
									"type": "text",
									"text": "From your explanations I understood the "
								},
								{
									"type": "text",
									"marks": [
										{
											"type": "bold"
										}
									],
									"text": "overview of sessions in Django"
								},
								{
									"type": "text",
									"text": ", especially that session is like server-side memory which uses a session ID stored in the browser cookie to link to data in the session table. I also grasped that the table contains fields such as session key, encoded data, and expiration, and that middleware automatically handles loading and saving sessions. I didn’t learn every low-level detail, but I now understand the big picture: session works like a dictionary stored on the server and accessed through request.session, while Django manages storage and retrieval behind the scenes."
								}
							]
						}
					]
				}
			},
			"parentId": "page:GIWjejKyyVPYplg8S9Trk",
